&NewLine;

One last happy night at a healthy hotel in Finland

On a carpet of grass and buttercups amid a forest of tall pines 3 km from the small Finnish town [GAP id=77]1 p. it shares [GAP id=78] 1 p. name, Paimio is a clean-lined architectural masterpiece by the godfather of Finnish functionalism, Alvar Aalto.

&NewLine;

Paimio has a Riviera flair at odds [GAP id=79] 1 p. elements of its oral tradition. As one-time resident Kaarlo Aitomäki wrote in his diary: “This house contains more suffering than any other. Hospitals are different. You only spend a short time in them. But here you stay month after month, even years. And you have no idea [GAP id=80] 1 p. you are going to get better or die. The mortuary is always waiting there in the forest.” The complex had its own morgue, stationed at a respectful distance and [GAP id=81] 1 p. as the Rose Cellar.

&NewLine;

Paimio is [GAP id=82] 1 p. surviving example of a sanatorium, an isolated residential facility for the treatment of long-term illness from the era when bed rest and healing sunlight were [GAP id=83] 1 p. first line of defence against disease.

&NewLine;

There has been little call for sanatoria since [GAP id=84] 1 p., so Paimio became a general hospital in the 60’s, then a residential rehabilitation centre for children and families, which is currently [GAP id=85] 1 p. and relocated. As various attempts to secure the building’s future [GAP id=86] 1 p., my stay potentially constitutes the last ever opportunity to sleep in conditions experienced by the original residents.

